STS is a security token service that provide a APIs to get a temporary security token to perform operation on cloud.
It is used with certain role that can be assumnd by any other IAM role, IAM User, aws Service, SAML user, federated user erc.
Magically withh this you can perform operation on AWS without any actual IAM user or direct IAM role. with just a fzcebook id and a assumable IAM role i can
do operation on AWS.

APIs of STS:Assume* always return  below items
    {
      "Credentials": {
        "AccessKeyId": "ASIA...",
        "SecretAccessKey": "...",
        "SessionToken": "...",
        "Expiration": "2026-07-21T..."
      }
    }
These are short lived token that can be used for AWS operations.

STS:AssumeRole  :-
  This one provide the access tokes for any other IAM user, IAM role or AWS service. with IAM user "mufazzal" you can assume role "r1" and perform anu operation that r1 allow to do.
  DO note that IAM user "mufazzal" must have permission to call STS:AssumeRole
CMD to assume role:-
  aws sts assume-role --role-arn "arn:aws:iam::637460932892:role/vendor1-cross-account-role" --role-session-name "vendor-x-access" --external-id "iammufvendor1" --profile muf_personal_vendor1
  Passing external id add a check to make sure correct user is using it. this check should also be there in Condition of trust policy of Role "r1"


How to use this keys and token:-
    1. You can set it to env variable like
            $env:AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID = "ASIA..."
            $env:AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY = "..."
            $env:AWS_SESSION_TOKEN = "..."
    2. Set it in .aws/credentia file
        [my_asumed_role]
            aws_access_key_id=..
            aws_secret_access_key=...
            aws_session_token="........"
